@l0I0I0I0 no, you miss the point, the 11mm is designed to stretch during an impact and absorb some of the collision so you are less unlikely to receive serious harm from the forces of the seatbelt pressing against you during an impact. If there wasn't any stretch you would be thrown at high speed into the the belt and when the belt pulls back on you the force will be almost as bad as an impact against the windscreen or dashboard, only less so because of the momentum being contained. The belt is still going to age, possibly faster because of the elasticity and when it does that elasticity will be gone.

Buying a used car? Change the belts especially if it's over 10 years old, had child seats in it (except ISO-fix as these do not require seatbelts to work safely) or if you do not know the history of the car.

Personally, I think all cars being sold second hand should have compulsory replacement seatbelts fitted by a garage and certified by them unless theseatvelts are 3 years old just because of how they work, the difference between serious and minor injuries, or in worst case death (yes bad seatbelts can cause worse damage to you than without.
